title: note-xerox-alto
summary: The Xerox Alto (1973) — first computer designed around a graphical desktop; never sold but influenced everything that followed
tags: HistoryOfComputing
year: 1973
period: The GUI

Built at Xerox PARC. Introduced the bitmap display, the mouse as primary input device, the desktop metaphor (icons, overlapping windows), and Ethernet networking — all in one machine, years before any of these appeared commercially. It ran Smalltalk, the first fully object-oriented programming environment. Xerox never commercialised it effectively. Steve Jobs saw it in 1979; the Lisa (1983) and Macintosh (1984) followed. Bill Atkinson and Andy Hertzfeld, the Mac's primary engineers, have said the Alto was the direct inspiration.
